<section xml:id="Section-Dot-Product-and-its-Properties" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Dot Product and its Properties</title>

  <definition xml:id="def-dotproduct">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathbf{u}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m> be vectors in <m>\R^n</m>.  
        The <term>dot product</term> of <m>\mathbf{u}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, denoted by <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot \mathbf{v}</m>, is given by
        <me>
          \mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}u_1\\u_2\\\vdots\\u_n\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}v_1\\v_2\\\vdots\\v_n\end{bmatrix}=u_1v_1+u_2v_2+\ldots+u_nv_n.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example xml:id="ex-dotex">
    <p>
      Find <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot \mathbf{v}</m> if <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\\-4\end{bmatrix}</m>. 
      <me>
          \mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\\-4\end{bmatrix}=(-2)(3)+(0)(2)+(1)(-4)=-6-4=-10
      </me>
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    Note that the dot product of two vectors is a scalar.  For this reason, the dot product is sometimes called a <term>scalar product</term>.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="Subsection-Properties-of-the-Dot-Product">
    <title>Properties of the Dot Product</title>

    <p>
      A quick examination of Example \ref{ex:dotex} will convince you that the dot product is <term>commutative</term>. 
      In other words, <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{u}</m>.  
      This and other properties of the dot product are stated below.
    </p>
    
  </subsection>


<theorem xml:id="th-dotproductproperties">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The following properties hold for vectors <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> and scalar <m>k</m> in <m>\R</m>.
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="item-commutative">
          <p> <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{u}</m> </p>
        </li>
    
   
  <li>
    <p>
    </p>
</li>\label{item:distributive} <m>(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})\cdot \mathbf{w}=\mathbf{u}\cdot \mathbf{w}+\mathbf{v}\cdot \mathbf{w}</m>
   
  <li>
    <p>
    </p>
</li>\label{item:distributive-again} <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot (\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w})=\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{u}\cdot \mathbf{w}</m>
   
  <li>
    <p>
    </p>
</li>\label{item:scalar} <m>(k\mathbf{u})\cdot \mathbf{v}=k(\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{v})=\mathbf{u}\cdot (k\mathbf{v})</m>
   
  <li>
    <p>
    </p>
</li> \label{item:positive} <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{u}\geq 0</m>, and <m>\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{u}=0</m> if and only if <m>\mathbf{u}={\bf 0}</m>.
   
  <li>
    <p>
    </p>
</li> \label{item:norm}
    <m>\norm{\mathbf{u}}^2=\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{u}</m>
  </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>

We will prove Property ~\ref{item:distributive}.  The remaining properties are left as exercises.

<proof>
    <p>[Proof of Property~\ref{item:distributive}:]

\begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}\right)\cdot \mathbf{w}\amp=\left(\begin{bmatrix} u_1\\ u_2\\ \vdots\\ u_n \end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix} v_1\\ v_2\\ \vdots\\ v_n \end{bmatrix}\right)\cdot \begin{bmatrix}w_1\\w_2\\\vdots\\w_n\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}
u_1+v_1\\
u_2+v_2\\
\vdots\\
u_n+v_n
\end{bmatrix}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}w_1\\w_2\\\vdots\\w_n\end{bmatrix}\\
\amp=(u_1+v_1)w_1+
(u_2+v_2)w_2+
\ldots+
(u_n+v_n)w_n\\
\amp=u_1w_1+v_1w_1+
u_2w_2+v_2w_2+
\ldots+
u_nw_n+v_nw_n\\
\amp=(u_1w_1+
u_2w_2\ldots+u_nw_n)+(v_1w_1+v_2w_2+
\ldots
+v_nw_n)\\
\amp=\begin{bmatrix}
u_1\\
u_2\\
\vdots\\
u_n
\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}w_1\\w_2\\\vdots\\w_n\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}
v_1\\
v_2\\
\vdots\\
v_n
\end{bmatrix}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}w_1\\w_2\\\vdots\\w_n\end{bmatrix}
=\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{w}+\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{w}
\end{align*}
    </p>
</proof>

We will illustrate Property~\ref{item:norm} with an example.
<example>
    <p>\label{ex:exprop6}
  Let <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\3\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Use <m>\mathbf{u}</m> to illustrate Property~\ref{item:norm} of Theorem~\ref{th:dotproductproperties}.
  \begin{explanation}
  
  
<me>
    \norm{\mathbf{u}}^2=(-2)^2+3^2=(-2)(-2)+(3)(3)=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\3\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}-2\\3\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{u}\cdot\mathbf{u}
</me>

  \end{explanation}
    </p>
</example>

If we take the square root of both sides of the equation in Property~\ref{item:norm}, we get an alternative way to think of the \href{https://ximera.osu.edu/oerlinalg/LinearAlgebra/VEC-0020/main}{length of a vector}.

<corollary>
    <statement>
        <p>[Length of a Vector]\label{cor:length_via_dotprod}
    Let <m>\mathbf{v}</m> be a vector in <m>\R^n</m>, then the <term>length</term>, or the <term>magnitude</term>, of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is given by
<me> \label{eq:norm_dotp} 
\norm{\mathbf{v}}=\sqrt{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{v}}
</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>

